WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.960
Hey everyone, we're from the Posit Support team and we're going to show you how to run,

00:00:11.960 --> 00:00:19.400
in this case a Shiny application on Workbench through the Linux command line.

00:00:19.400 --> 00:00:23.840
So this can be particularly useful when you're troubleshooting an issue and you want to figure

00:00:23.840 --> 00:00:31.400
out if it's a Workbench problem or a problem with your underlying R installation of the Linux server.

00:00:31.400 --> 00:00:37.279
So you'll see we have this Shiny app that we can just run, which works.

00:00:37.279 --> 00:00:48.040
Now, if we were to run this via the Linux command line, we need to run R and preload the command here,

00:00:48.040 --> 00:00:57.880
which is so you run R interactively and you specify path to the Shiny application,

00:00:57.880 --> 00:01:04.199
in which case it's in our user's home directory for the demo and the project is called Demo Shiny.

00:01:04.199 --> 00:01:12.360
If we run that, we'll see we'll get a listening on port and we can just type this into the web browser.

00:01:12.360 --> 00:01:17.839
And when we do that, we should see that the app runs as expected.

00:01:17.839 --> 00:01:23.239
So if we're running into issues with the app on either Workbench or the Linux command line,

00:01:23.239 --> 00:01:31.680
so we know where to troubleshoot further or where we can go, whether to focus on the Workbench side or focus on the Linux side.

